<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06073217 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06073217 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  POLICE; ANIMAL; DRUG; TRAINING; MILPITAS  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  It's time for a Milpitas canine team to bone up.;    The police departmentwill send a police officer and a police dog to Adlerhorst International, aRiverside-based police dog handler training school, to learn how to detectnarcotics.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MILPITAS POLICE DOG TO GET DRUG TRAINING  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     More than 120 law enforcement agencies throughout the country use dogstrained at Adlerhorst, the largest private training school in the world forpolice dogs and their handlers.;    Police Chief Frank Acosta said thedepartment will screen canine teams to see which officers are interested inthe program and which dogs would be most likely to succeed.;    Acosta saidthe city's four canine teams are used for searches but not for crowd control.;   In a letter distributed last week to the city council, Acosta wrote, &quot;Theneed for a narcotic detection canine team is evident due to suspects dealingin the sales of narcotics who have resorted to hiding or disguising theirnarcotics by modifying vehicles, residences and other personal items.&quot;;   Mayor Pete &quot;Primo&quot; McHugh said, &quot;That's going to be money very well spent.&quot;The council authorized the department to spend up to $5,000 to coverregistration, travel and meals for the four-week session.;    Milpitas plansto send its own dog to Adlerhorst, although the school has dogs available fordepartments that do not supply their own. &quot;They'll provide the dog, but thecost is like $5,000,&quot; Acosta said. &quot;It's very expensive.&quot;;    The dogs thatAdlerhorst sells are pre-trained in Europe and respond only to commands inDutch.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  RICH RAMIREZ, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME